                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18420613-2020-offence-1 t18420613-name-1520"></join>John Smith</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420613-name-1521" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1521" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1521" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1521" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN SMITH</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Little Canterbury-place, Lambeth. On the 3rd of June the prisoner came to my house with a cask of wine and some fur<lb></lb>niture—he charged 20<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for the carriage—we had a dispute about its being more than it ought to be—I paid him the 20<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and said I should give him a</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184206130250"></xptr>
               <p>note to say that it was too much—he said he would take the things back—he threw the money on the table—I wrote the memorandum in his book, and during that time he took up the 20<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. and two half crowns, two shillings, and a sixpence besides, which laid on the table—there was no pretence for saying that was part of his moneys—he only demanded 20<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I was finishing a letter—there were letters on the table—I said to my servant, "Is the man gone?"—she looked through the window and said, "He is gone"—I am sure the two half-crowns and two shilling, and sixpence had been on the table—the money I gave the prisoner was a half-sovereign, a five-shilling-piece, and two half-crowns—that was a my left hand, and the other money on my right hand.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Why did not you stop him <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I had a number of papers on the table when he came in, I was writing for the evening post—as soon as he was gone I gathered up the papers, looked for the money, and it was gone—I missed my money about a mi<lb></lb>nute and a half after he was gone—I sent my servant after him—there was no other man with him when he received the money—there was during part of the time—he refused to leave the goods unless I signed the book and paid him the 20<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I did not say I would not pay him more than 17<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I said nothing about 17<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—he threw the money on the table himself, and said he would take back the goods—I afterwards sent my sister-in-law to Pick ford's—I did not desire her to say that she had no doubt that a mistake had occurred, by my having had a part of the money at the time in my hand, which I unthinkingly handed to the prisooer—I never desired her to say any such thing—I went to Pickford's the next morning—I bad an interview with the prisoner there—I did not ask whether 20<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. was the charge he was directed to make—I afterwards complained that 20<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. was more than he ought to have charged, but not in the first instance—I will not swear that I did at all.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You must know whether you found that the 20<hi rend="italic">s.</hi> was a wrong charge? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It was a wrong charge decidedly, which I intend to put them in the Court for—it is an overcharge—I do not mean to say it was a wrong charge on his part—I did not say to the prisoner, when I went to Pickford's the next morning, that unless he gave me the 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. I would give him into custody—I said nothing of the kind—I said, "You took 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. yesterday that was not your own"—he said, "I did no such thing"—I said, "Then I shall give you into custody"—f sent my sister-in law for a policeman, and the moment I did so some of the clerks there did their best to get him out of the place—they sent him to another part of the office, and I followed him—the prisoner told me he had only received the right money; so did the clerks—he did not say he would refund no<lb></lb>thing—I swear he never said so—I do not recollect his saying he would not give me any thing back—I believe he did not.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420613-name-1522" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1522" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1522" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1522" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>ELIZABETH SMITH</persName>
                  </hi>. I remember the prisoner coming with this parcel from Pickford's—I went down to open the door—he gave me a paper, and delivered the parcels—I gave it to my brother—they disputed about the price—he said he would pay him, but he would not sign the book—be wrote a note, and wished the prisoner to sign it—he said he had nothing to do with his notes, he would sign his own book—my brother said be would not sign it, he would pay him the money—he said, "I can't take the money, unless you sign my book"—he threw down the money that was given him—my brother said, "I will sign your book;" and while he</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184206130251"></xptr>
               <p>was writing, the prisoner cleared the table of all the money—there was 27<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. on the table, I am sure of that, 17<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in silver and 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. in gold—it was a short distance apart—I cannot say how much was in one lot, and how much in the other—I was not at the table—no one was near the table but my brother.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examinedQ.</hi> Did you go that night to Mr. Pickford's? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I did—I saw two gentlemen there—I said I wished to see the prisoner, in order that the mistake might be rectified—one of the gentlemen said the prisoner would not be on the wharf till the following morning, and if I would call in the morning the matter should be inquired into—when I went away I said, "I suppose we must trust to this man's honesty, as the money was not marked"—the gentleman did not say, "No, if we are satisfied he has received more than he ought, we will take care that the matter shall be rectified"—he said no such words—I went the next morning, accom<lb></lb>panied by my brother, to the wharf—I again saw the persons I had seen over-night; I also saw the prisoner—he was not there at first; they fetched him—my brother did not threaten him that unless he gave him the 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi> 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. be would give him in charge—he said, "What money did you take away last night?"—he said," 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>."—my brother said, "No more?"—he said, "No"—my brother turned to me and said, "Fetch a policeman"—I went and got one. <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">called</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420613-name-1523" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1523" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1523" type="surname" value="WOODCOCK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1523" type="given" value="DAVID"></interp>DAVID WOODCOCK</persName>
                  </hi>. I am clerk to Messrs. Pickfords. I remember Elisabeth Smith coming to the wharf on the evening in question—she told me her brother had paid 27<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. instead of 20<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. by mistake, and she wished to see the prisoner, in order that she might arrange it with him—I said he was not there then, and told her at what time he would be there——she said," I suppose I must depend on the man"; honesty and recollec<lb></lb>tion for the purpose of repaying the money"—I said, "No; if we are satisfied he has received more than he ought, I will take care the matter shall beset right"—I did not in any way endeavour to secrete the prisoner, or get him out of the way—the firm would not sanction any thing of the kind—he has been three years and a half in their employ, and is a man of honesty and merit, and has given satisfaction in every way.</p>
